{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"55d54378-9e16-4b9e-9cab-3fc0e4c8e435","content":"Use the `--filter` flag with a single expression combining both conditions via `&`:\n\n```\ndotnet test --filter \"ClassName~Integration & Category=Smoke\"\n```\n\n**How it works:**\n\n| Part | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `ClassName~Integration` | Class name **contains** \"Integration\" |\n| `&` | Logical AND |\n| `Category=Smoke` | xUnit trait `Category` **equals** \"Smoke\" |\n\nThis assumes your Smoke tests are decorated with `[Trait(\"Category\", \"Smoke\")]`. The `~` operator means \"contains\", while `=` means \"exact match\".","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"99d862fe-6f8e-40b0-84f0-e2b5b9c87d87","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to construct a single combined filter expression for `dotnet test` that:\n\n1. Runs only tests with category \"Smoke\" (or trait \"Category=Smoke\")\n2. Only from test classes whose name contains \"Integration\"\n\nIn xUnit v3 with `dotnet test`, you use the `--filter` flag with a single expression. The filter syntax supports:\n\n- `FullyQualifiedName` — matches the full test name (namespace.class.method)\n- `DisplayName` — matches the display name\n- `Category` — matches xUnit traits with key \"Category\"\n- `ClassName` — matches the class name\n\n\n- `ClassName~Integration` means ClassName contains \"Integration\"\n- `Category=Smoke` means the Category trait equals \"Smoke\"\n- `&` is the AND operator\n\nSo the combined filter expression would be `dotnet test --filter \"ClassName~Integration & Category=Smoke\"` to run only tests from classes containing \"Integration\" that have the Smoke category trait.","outputTokens":433,"requestId":"1BDD:AAEEE:4B53E3:55ECD7:6A03D64B"},"id":"6352521e-852d-4215-be32-ef843bfa24b7","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:39:32.633Z","parentId":"e8c25160-58f3-4f97-a9f4-e3ac29171c5c"}
